1
00:02:24,840 --> 00:02:26,990
[buzzing]

2
00:02:27,200 --> 00:02:30,875
[man] <i>They will say</i>
<i>that I have shed innocent blood.</i>

3
00:02:33,120 --> 00:02:35,111
<i>What's blood for</i>

4
00:02:35,320 --> 00:02:37,356
<i>if not for shedding?</i>

5
00:02:39,080 --> 00:02:41,469
<i>With my hook for a hand,</i>

6
00:02:41,680 --> 00:02:45,992
<i>I'll split you from your groin</i>
<i>to your gullet.</i>

7
00:02:51,960 --> 00:02:53,916
[woman's scream]

8
00:03:05,840 --> 00:03:09,515
[man] <i>I came for you.</i>

9
00:03:16,000 --> 00:03:19,549
[girl] It's the scariest story
I have ever heard, and it's true.

10
00:03:19,760 --> 00:03:23,309
<i>It happened a few years ago</i>
<i>near Moses Lake in Indiana.</i>

11
00:03:23,520 --> 00:03:25,875
<i>Clara was babysitting for the Johnsons.</i>

12
00:03:26,080 --> 00:03:29,356
<i>And Billy pulls up on his motorcycle.</i>

13
00:03:29,560 --> 00:03:33,838
<i>She wasn't going out with Billy</i>
<i>but with Michael for about six months.</i>

14
00:03:34,040 --> 00:03:39,160
<i>But she always had the hots for Billy</i>
<i>cos he was like, a bad boy.</i>

15
00:03:39,360 --> 00:03:42,079
<i>And Michael was just... so nice.</i>

16
00:03:42,280 --> 00:03:45,590
<i>So, anyway,</i>
<i>she decides that tonight's the night</i>

17
00:03:45,800 --> 00:03:49,031
<i>that she's gonna give Billy</i>
<i>what she never gave to Michael.</i>

18
00:03:49,240 --> 00:03:52,232
- Have you ever heard of Candyman?
- No.

19
00:03:52,440 --> 00:03:55,716
Well, his right hand is sawn off.

20
00:03:55,920 --> 00:03:58,753
He has a hook
jammed in the bloody stump.

21
00:04:00,240 --> 00:04:04,233
And if you look in the mirror
and you say his name five times,

22
00:04:05,960 --> 00:04:09,077
he'll appear behind you
breathing down your neck.

23
00:04:09,280 --> 00:04:11,236
You wanna try it?

24
00:04:13,960 --> 00:04:15,916
[girl] <i>So Billy began.</i>

25
00:04:16,120 --> 00:04:19,510
<i>- He looked in the mirror and he said...</i>
- Candyman.

26
00:04:21,600 --> 00:04:23,556
Candyman.

27
00:04:25,400 --> 00:04:27,356
Candyman.

28
00:04:28,760 --> 00:04:30,716
Candyman.

29
00:04:36,160 --> 00:04:38,116
No one ever got past four.

30
00:04:40,960 --> 00:04:43,030
Not here.

31
00:04:43,240 --> 00:04:46,755
Go downstairs.
I have a surprise for you.

32
00:04:50,440 --> 00:04:52,396
[chuckles]

33
00:04:55,160 --> 00:04:58,152
[girl] <i>She looked in the mirror and,</i>
<i>I don't know why,</i>

34
00:04:58,360 --> 00:05:00,669
<i>but she said his name the last time.</i>

35
00:05:00,880 --> 00:05:02,836
Candyman.

36
00:05:03,040 --> 00:05:04,996
<i>She turned out the lights...</i>

37
00:05:05,200 --> 00:05:07,156
[piercing scream]

38
00:05:08,800 --> 00:05:11,360
What he saw
turned his hair white from shock.

39
00:05:12,320 --> 00:05:15,915
Killed her, split her open with his hook

40
00:05:16,120 --> 00:05:18,509
and then killed the baby too.

41
00:05:18,720 --> 00:05:21,280
Billy got away, but

42
00:05:21,480 --> 00:05:23,436
soon after, he went crazy.

43
00:05:24,480 --> 00:05:28,189
My roommate's boyfriend knows him.

44
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:36,309
So, when did you first hear this story?

45
00:05:36,520 --> 00:05:39,273
My friend heard it on the radio.
It's sick.

46
00:05:39,480 --> 00:05:43,359
The babysitter just roasted the kid,
like it was a turkey or something.

47
00:05:44,520 --> 00:05:48,718
So, what's the deal? You guys doing
a page on serial killers or something?

48
00:05:48,920 --> 00:05:52,515
- Something like that.
- That's it. We're done.

49
00:05:52,720 --> 00:05:54,472
- All right.
- Thanks.

50
00:05:54,680 --> 00:05:55,999
No problem.

51
00:05:56,200 --> 00:05:57,679
- See ya.
- See ya.

52
00:06:00,080 --> 00:06:02,799
- See ya.
- [both giggle]

53
00:06:03,000 --> 00:06:05,070
They get younger every day.

54
00:06:08,320 --> 00:06:12,154
[man] Does anybody remember
the craze for pet baby alligators?

55
00:06:12,360 --> 00:06:15,796
[girl] When they got big,
people flushed them down the toilet.

56
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:19,913
They live in the sewers now.
Some of them are 30 feet long.

57
00:06:20,120 --> 00:06:22,076
[man] Where did this happen?

58
00:06:22,280 --> 00:06:25,750
[girl] Miami. They went blind
from living in the dark.

59
00:06:25,960 --> 00:06:26,915
[laughter]

60
00:06:27,120 --> 00:06:30,829
[boy] It wasn't Miami, it was New York.
I read it in the paper.

61
00:06:31,040 --> 00:06:34,112
- Then it must be true.
- [laughter]

62
00:06:34,320 --> 00:06:39,030
Why would Danny and Diane both
be suffering from the same delusion

63
00:06:39,240 --> 00:06:41,231
in two cities 1,000 miles apart?

64
00:06:43,280 --> 00:06:48,479
Let's face it, folks.
There are no alligators in the sewers.

65
00:06:48,680 --> 00:06:53,549
No, it's round the campfire,
it's bedtime stories.

66
00:06:53,760 --> 00:06:58,311
These stories are modern, oral folklore.

67
00:06:58,520 --> 00:07:03,036
They are the unselfconscious reflection
of the fears of urban society.

68
00:07:03,240 --> 00:07:05,595
- [bell]
- That's lunch.

69
00:07:22,880 --> 00:07:24,632
[man]... primordial reptile.

70
00:07:24,840 --> 00:07:26,796
It's a monster, right? Why?

71
00:07:29,520 --> 00:07:31,795
Ouch. Ooh. Eugh.

72
00:07:32,000 --> 00:07:34,912
- Ah, the dashing professor.
- The lovely wife.

73
00:07:35,120 --> 00:07:36,951
Hello.

74
00:07:37,160 --> 00:07:42,598
Helen, the crème de la crème.
Harold, Diane, Daniel, Stacey.

75
00:07:42,800 --> 00:07:44,756
- Hi.
- Hello.

76
00:07:45,520 --> 00:07:48,751
Keep up the good work.
Thanks for your contributions.

77
00:07:48,960 --> 00:07:50,837
- Thanks. Bye.
- See you.

78
00:07:52,640 --> 00:07:53,595
Bye.

79
00:07:58,200 --> 00:07:59,269
See ya.

80
00:08:04,200 --> 00:08:08,751
So you wanna tell me about this girl?
What's her name? Stacey.

81
00:08:08,960 --> 00:08:13,112
She could barely look me in the eyes,
Trevor, and I swear she was blushing.

82
00:08:13,320 --> 00:08:16,596
Well, I guess that's because
she's madly in love with me.

83
00:08:16,800 --> 00:08:19,360
All those bursting adolescent hormones.

84
00:08:21,200 --> 00:08:24,510
- You don't really think...
- No, of course not.

85
00:08:24,720 --> 00:08:28,508
Good. I should hope not.
So, what's the matter?

86
00:08:29,560 --> 00:08:31,232
Trevor...

87
00:08:31,440 --> 00:08:34,910
You said you wouldn't do urban legends
until next semester.

88
00:08:35,120 --> 00:08:39,716
You knew Bernadette and I were gathering
data. Why did you have to ruin it?

89
00:08:39,920 --> 00:08:43,276
Honey, you can't expect me
to hold up their education

90
00:08:43,480 --> 00:08:46,119
while the two of you
complete your thesis.

91
00:08:46,320 --> 00:08:48,914
- I have a curriculum to follow.
- Yes, I know.

92
00:08:49,120 --> 00:08:51,839
Well? So don't be mad at me.

93
00:08:56,360 --> 00:09:00,035
[girl on tape] <i>If you look in the</i>
<i>mirror and say his name five times,</i>

94
00:09:00,240 --> 00:09:02,993
<i>he'll appear behind you</i>
<i>breathing down your neck.</i>

95
00:09:12,480 --> 00:09:15,438
- Can I clean the room?
- Oh, sure. Don't mind me.

96
00:09:15,640 --> 00:09:18,950
<i>So Billy began.</i>
<i>He looked in the mirror and he said,</i>

97
00:09:19,160 --> 00:09:22,550
<i>"Candyman, Candyman, Candyman..."</i>

98
00:09:25,880 --> 00:09:27,836
Candyman, huh?

99
00:09:28,040 --> 00:09:31,077
- Have you heard of him?
- Mm-hmm. You doin' a study on him?

100
00:09:33,000 --> 00:09:34,991
Yes, I am. What have you heard?

101
00:09:35,200 --> 00:09:38,317
Everybody's scared of him
once it gets dark.

102
00:09:38,520 --> 00:09:41,876
He live over at Cabrini.
My friend told me about him.

103
00:09:42,080 --> 00:09:44,674
- Cabrini-Green?
- Yeah, in the projects.

104
00:09:44,880 --> 00:09:48,668
I don't know too much about it,
but my friend, she know all about it.

105
00:09:48,880 --> 00:09:50,836
Her cousin live at Cabrini.

106
00:09:51,040 --> 00:09:53,349
They say he killed a lady.

107
00:09:53,560 --> 00:09:55,869
- Can I talk to you friend?
- Sure.

108
00:10:01,360 --> 00:10:03,749
- Kitty?
- Yeah? What do you want?

109
00:10:03,960 --> 00:10:07,873
- Lady down here wanna talk to you.
- All right.

110
00:10:09,040 --> 00:10:10,996
She comin'.

111
00:10:15,800 --> 00:10:16,755
I'm Helen Lyle.

112
00:10:16,960 --> 00:10:19,030
Pleased to meet you.
Henrietta Mosely.

113
00:10:19,240 --> 00:10:21,196
- And this is Kitty Culver.
- Hello.

114
00:10:21,920 --> 00:10:23,876
Tell her about the Candyman.

115
00:10:24,080 --> 00:10:29,108
All I know was there was some lady
in a tub, and she heard a noise.

116
00:10:29,320 --> 00:10:33,313
- Do you remember her name?
- I think her name was Ruthie Jean.

117
00:10:33,520 --> 00:10:37,718
She heard this bangin' like somebody
was tryin' to make a hole in the wall.

118
00:10:37,920 --> 00:10:42,311
So Ruthie called 911 and said there's
somebody comin' through the walls.

119
00:10:42,520 --> 00:10:44,397
They didn't believe her.

120
00:10:44,600 --> 00:10:46,556
- They thought she was crazy.
- Mm-hm.

121
00:10:46,760 --> 00:10:50,878
So she called 911 again,
and they still didn't believe her.

122
00:10:51,080 --> 00:10:54,197
When they finally got there,
she was dead.

123
00:10:54,400 --> 00:10:57,790
- Was she shot?
- No...

124
00:10:58,000 --> 00:11:01,675
Um, she was killed with a hook.
[makes slicing sound]

125
00:11:03,160 --> 00:11:05,549
It's true.
Yeah, it is.

126
00:11:05,760 --> 00:11:08,877
I read it in the papers.
Candyman killed her.

127
00:11:10,640 --> 00:11:14,519
Yeah, but I don't know
nothin' about that.

128
00:12:11,400 --> 00:12:14,119
This is sick.
This isn't a fairytale.

129
00:12:14,320 --> 00:12:16,675
A woman got killed here. Jesus.

130
00:12:16,880 --> 00:12:19,155
That's not the half of it.

131
00:12:20,800 --> 00:12:23,712
That's Cabrini-Green,
not that you'd recognize it.

132
00:12:23,920 --> 00:12:26,388
No kidding.
I won't even drive past there.

133
00:12:26,600 --> 00:12:29,512
- A kid got shot there the other day.
- Every day.

134
00:12:29,720 --> 00:12:32,473
Look carefully at this picture.

135
00:12:32,680 --> 00:12:34,636
And then this one.

136
00:12:41,560 --> 00:12:43,516
You spot it?

137
00:12:44,480 --> 00:12:45,879
No.

138
00:12:46,080 --> 00:12:50,551
That's not Cabrini-Green.
That's this building, Lincoln Village.

139
00:12:50,760 --> 00:12:53,320
My apartment was built
as a housing project.

140
00:12:54,360 --> 00:12:56,635
- No?
- Yeah.

141
00:12:56,840 --> 00:12:58,796
Now take a look at this.

142
00:13:08,680 --> 00:13:13,390
The city realized there was no barrier
between here and the Gold Coast.

143
00:13:13,600 --> 00:13:17,115
Unlike the highway and the El train
to keep the ghetto cut off.

144
00:13:17,320 --> 00:13:19,709
Exactly.
So they made some alterations.

145
00:13:19,920 --> 00:13:24,596
They covered the cinder block in plaster
and sold the lot off as condos.

146
00:13:24,800 --> 00:13:28,588
- How much did you pay for this place?
- Don't ask.

147
00:13:31,320 --> 00:13:33,276
Now wait till you see this.

148
00:13:35,720 --> 00:13:37,676
Here's the proof.

149
00:13:42,240 --> 00:13:44,196
The killer, or killers,

150
00:13:44,840 --> 00:13:48,389
they don't know which, smashed through
the back of this cabinet.

151
00:13:48,600 --> 00:13:50,556
See, there's no wall there.

152
00:13:50,760 --> 00:13:54,150
Only a medicine chest
separates us from the other apartment.

153
00:13:55,680 --> 00:13:58,114
There could be somebody on the toilet!

154
00:13:58,320 --> 00:14:01,630
- The apartment's vacant.
- Are you sure?

155
00:14:02,680 --> 00:14:04,033
There.

156
00:14:04,880 --> 00:14:06,836
OK. Now take a look.

157
00:14:10,400 --> 00:14:12,789
That is amazing.

158
00:14:13,000 --> 00:14:15,230
- What?
- I saw a light go on.

159
00:14:15,440 --> 00:14:17,396
There's nobody there.

160
00:14:17,920 --> 00:14:19,876
- Psyche.
- That's not funny.

161
00:14:22,600 --> 00:14:24,909
- You didn't scare me at all.
- Yeah, right.

162
00:14:30,880 --> 00:14:33,314
You don't believe all
that nonsense, do you?

163
00:14:33,520 --> 00:14:35,590
I don't. Do you?

164
00:14:35,800 --> 00:14:36,755
No.

165
00:14:39,200 --> 00:14:40,679
All right.

166
00:14:40,880 --> 00:14:43,952
Candyman, Candyman, Candyman,

167
00:14:44,160 --> 00:14:46,116
Candyman...

168
00:14:48,960 --> 00:14:50,916
Candyman.

169
00:14:51,880 --> 00:14:53,836
Oh, you chicken!

170
00:14:54,040 --> 00:14:56,235
You have to do it five times.
Go again.

171
00:14:56,440 --> 00:14:58,396
[giggling]

172
00:15:15,120 --> 00:15:17,076
[rustling]

173
00:15:20,120 --> 00:15:21,075
Trevor?

174
00:15:27,960 --> 00:15:29,916
[muffled screaming]

175
00:15:31,680 --> 00:15:34,638
- Oh, Trevor!
- What? Who were you expecting?

176
00:15:36,560 --> 00:15:40,189
- What time is it?
- It's late, and I'm smashed.

177
00:15:42,280 --> 00:15:44,236
Sorry I scared you.

178
00:16:16,920 --> 00:16:19,992
What's with the arsenal?
We're only going eight blocks.

179
00:16:20,200 --> 00:16:24,273
- You got us dressed up like cops.
- I just said dress conservatively.

180
00:16:24,480 --> 00:16:26,755
No, we look like cops.

181
00:16:26,960 --> 00:16:29,394
- Why are you trying to scare me?
- I'm not.

182
00:16:29,600 --> 00:16:33,957
I just want you to know the gangs
hold this whole neighborhood hostage.

183
00:16:36,680 --> 00:16:38,636
OK, let's just turn around.

184
00:16:38,840 --> 00:16:42,230
We can write a boring thesis
regurgitating all the usual crap

185
00:16:42,440 --> 00:16:45,318
about urban legend.

186
00:16:48,720 --> 00:16:51,632
We've got a real shot here, Bernadette.

187
00:16:51,840 --> 00:16:56,630
A community attributes the daily horrors
of their lives to a mythical figure.

188
00:16:58,080 --> 00:17:01,117
If Trevor and Archie were here,
would they chicken out?

189
00:17:01,320 --> 00:17:04,073
- In a second.
- Exactly.

190
00:17:06,160 --> 00:17:08,116
All right.

191
00:17:40,280 --> 00:17:42,236
[indistinct chatter]

192
00:17:49,440 --> 00:17:52,238
- You wanna wait here for me?
- No.

193
00:17:53,440 --> 00:17:55,396
Well, then let's go.

194
00:17:59,360 --> 00:18:02,079
- [boy] Check 'em out.
- [Helen] Lock the car.

195
00:18:05,760 --> 00:18:07,751
[boy] Hey, now.

196
00:18:07,960 --> 00:18:10,952
Want somethin', baby?
I got it for you.

197
00:18:11,160 --> 00:18:13,116
Say, yo, mama.
Come on, baby.

198
00:18:14,160 --> 00:18:16,549
- [laughing]
- Yo, baby.

199
00:18:17,640 --> 00:18:20,473
- Which way you goin'?
- Just going inside.

200
00:18:20,680 --> 00:18:22,033
Yeah?

201
00:18:22,680 --> 00:18:26,389
- You can't come up in here.
- Who you lookin' for?

202
00:18:26,600 --> 00:18:29,956
- Just going up to see a friend.
- Sure you're not the police?

203
00:18:30,160 --> 00:18:32,116
Look like Five-O to me.

204
00:18:32,920 --> 00:18:34,876
Ask blondie where she goin'.

205
00:18:35,080 --> 00:18:39,870
- Who you goin' to see?
- Let's take the stairs. Come on.

206
00:18:40,080 --> 00:18:42,036
Where you all goin' there?

207
00:18:45,000 --> 00:18:46,069
[whistling]

208
00:18:46,280 --> 00:18:50,353
Heads up, people.
Five-O comin' up the back door. Police!

209
00:18:51,200 --> 00:18:55,398
It's OK. They think we're cops.
They're not going to follow us.

210
00:19:01,480 --> 00:19:03,436
Hang on.

211
00:19:24,240 --> 00:19:26,196
- Look at this.
- This is great.

212
00:19:29,640 --> 00:19:31,596
[Bernadette] "Sweets to..."

213
00:19:33,080 --> 00:19:35,640
- [Helen] "The sweet."
- "Sweets to the sweet."

214
00:19:37,760 --> 00:19:40,593
- Hurry up, Helen.
- Lemme get the door.

215
00:19:43,440 --> 00:19:45,192
[barks]

216
00:19:48,360 --> 00:19:50,316
- Sorry.
- Jesus, Helen.

217
00:19:54,560 --> 00:19:56,869
- Here it is.
- Don't go in there.

218
00:20:00,280 --> 00:20:02,236
Come on.

219
00:20:04,600 --> 00:20:06,556
Jesus, it stinks.

220
00:20:14,320 --> 00:20:17,232
I was right.
The layout is identical.

221
00:20:17,440 --> 00:20:20,159
Which means that the bathroom
is over there.

222
00:20:20,360 --> 00:20:22,430
- Helen...
- What's the problem?

223
00:20:22,640 --> 00:20:24,596
A woman died in there.
Leave it.

224
00:20:33,040 --> 00:20:35,190
It's all right.
There's nothing to see.

225
00:20:45,040 --> 00:20:47,600
- Wait.
- This is where he broke through, right?

226
00:20:47,800 --> 00:20:48,755
Yeah.

227
00:20:55,400 --> 00:20:58,597
- Well, we found it. Let's go.
- Wait a second.

228
00:21:03,280 --> 00:21:05,236
OK. Hang onto this.

229
00:21:08,280 --> 00:21:10,271
I'm just gonna go through.

230
00:21:10,480 --> 00:21:12,948
- Then we're outta here.
- You're kidding.

231
00:21:13,160 --> 00:21:14,593
It's a derelict apartment.

232
00:21:14,800 --> 00:21:17,519
What if somebody's
packing drugs in there?

233
00:21:17,720 --> 00:21:21,030
You gonna apologize
and give 'em your card? Huh?

234
00:21:21,240 --> 00:21:23,196
All right. Let's listen.

235
00:21:29,720 --> 00:21:32,757
- There's nobody in there.
- OK.

236
00:21:32,960 --> 00:21:34,916
Hurry up. Be careful.

237
00:21:44,680 --> 00:21:46,796
Give me the camera.

238
00:21:47,000 --> 00:21:49,230
- You got five minutes.
- OK. Five.

239
00:22:46,280 --> 00:22:48,589
- [camera whirrs]
- Damn it.

240
00:23:32,440 --> 00:23:35,398
[metal door slams
in distance]

241
00:23:48,760 --> 00:23:50,910
Bernadette! Sorry.

242
00:23:51,120 --> 00:23:53,554
- I ran out of film. I gotta go back.
- No way.

243
00:23:53,760 --> 00:23:56,433
- You can't...
- No, way, Helen. We're outta here!

244
00:24:05,160 --> 00:24:08,152
- [dog barks]
- Hey, what y'all doin' in there?

245
00:24:08,360 --> 00:24:10,590
[Bernadette] We're just leaving.

246
00:24:10,800 --> 00:24:15,191
- You here for the sweets?
- No. We're not cops.

247
00:24:15,400 --> 00:24:18,790
- We're from the university.
- You don't belong here, lady.

248
00:24:19,000 --> 00:24:21,719
Goin' through people's apartments
and things.

249
00:24:21,920 --> 00:24:24,593
My name is Helen Lyle.
This is Bernadette Walsh.

250
00:24:24,800 --> 00:24:29,032
We're doing a thesis, and we were
wondering if we could talk to you.

251
00:24:29,680 --> 00:24:31,796
Here. This is my card.

252
00:24:35,960 --> 00:24:37,916
- [baby cries]
- My baby.

253
00:24:38,200 --> 00:24:40,156
Come on. Let's go.

254
00:24:44,760 --> 00:24:48,070
Whites don't ever come here,
'cept to cause us a problem.

255
00:24:48,280 --> 00:24:50,840
Believe me, that's not
what we want to do.

256
00:24:56,640 --> 00:24:58,596
[quietly] Let's go in.

257
00:25:07,120 --> 00:25:09,076
So you're doing a study?

258
00:25:10,320 --> 00:25:14,791
What you gonna say?
That we're bad? Hmm?

259
00:25:15,000 --> 00:25:18,117
We steal? We gang-bang?

260
00:25:18,720 --> 00:25:20,676
We all on drugs, right?

261
00:25:22,200 --> 00:25:24,839
We ain't all like
them assholes downstairs.

262
00:25:25,760 --> 00:25:27,716
I just wanna raise my child good.

263
00:25:28,960 --> 00:25:32,999
- He's a beautiful little boy.
- He's all I got.

264
00:25:33,200 --> 00:25:36,158
- What's his name?
- Anthony.

265
00:25:39,200 --> 00:25:40,758
I'm Anne-Marie.

266
00:25:43,680 --> 00:25:45,113
Anne-Marie McCoy.

267
00:25:45,320 --> 00:25:47,754
- Nice to meet you.
- Sorry we disturbed you.

268
00:25:47,960 --> 00:25:51,236
- We'll just get out of your way.
- It's OK.

269
00:25:51,440 --> 00:25:53,476
I don't mean to be rude. It's...

270
00:25:53,680 --> 00:25:57,036
You know, the white folks
that come round here

271
00:25:57,240 --> 00:25:59,196
ain't too handshakin' with us.

272
00:25:59,400 --> 00:26:00,719
[baby gurgles]

273
00:26:00,920 --> 00:26:03,070
- Hey, what you doin'?
- Let me help you.

274
00:26:05,640 --> 00:26:07,596
Making a mess here, huh?

275
00:26:08,800 --> 00:26:10,756
Thank you. Thanks.

276
00:26:11,920 --> 00:26:13,876
- You got kids?
- No, but I'd love one.

277
00:26:15,240 --> 00:26:16,798
Hey...

278
00:26:17,000 --> 00:26:19,195
Got my eye on this one, big time.

279
00:26:19,400 --> 00:26:22,551
Yeah.
They're not gonna get him.

280
00:26:32,520 --> 00:26:35,273
You wanna know about Ruthie Jean?

281
00:26:36,000 --> 00:26:40,278
They all been here, you know?
Newspapers, cops.

282
00:26:40,480 --> 00:26:44,359
Case workers. They all wanna know.

283
00:26:46,120 --> 00:26:48,076
I heard her screamin'.

284
00:26:50,760 --> 00:26:53,228
I heard her right through the walls.

285
00:26:54,120 --> 00:26:57,271
I dialed 911.
Nobody came.

286
00:26:58,360 --> 00:27:02,399
Nobody came.
Everybody scared.

287
00:27:03,200 --> 00:27:05,998
He come right through these walls,
you know?

288
00:27:06,600 --> 00:27:08,556
I-I'm scared.

289
00:27:09,920 --> 00:27:11,876
Scared for my child.

290
00:27:14,360 --> 00:27:17,716
- They ain't never gonna catch him.
- Who?

291
00:27:19,080 --> 00:27:20,513
Candyman.

292
00:27:20,720 --> 00:27:22,676
[laughter]

293
00:27:26,520 --> 00:27:29,557
[man] If they saw something they liked,
they'd point.

294
00:27:29,760 --> 00:27:32,320
They thought it was rude to point.

295
00:27:32,680 --> 00:27:35,990
- What did they do?
- They went... [grunts]

296
00:27:36,200 --> 00:27:38,760
Spat over people.
Quite extraordinary.

297
00:27:40,000 --> 00:27:42,833
- Be nice.
- I am being nice.

298
00:27:43,040 --> 00:27:46,828
So how are the two most beautiful
graduate students getting along?

299
00:27:47,040 --> 00:27:50,476
Trevor tells me you've been dabbling
in my favorite subject.

300
00:27:53,240 --> 00:27:56,596
I can't wait to review your data.
I can fit you in tomorrow.

301
00:27:56,800 --> 00:27:59,394
We're not ready yet.

302
00:27:59,600 --> 00:28:03,354
That's the moment at which
I can be of greatest assistance.

303
00:28:03,560 --> 00:28:07,439
Before you disappear down a path
to academic oblivia.

304
00:28:07,640 --> 00:28:10,359
- [Trevor] I think I've been there.
- [laughter]

305
00:28:10,560 --> 00:28:13,711
Actually, Purcell,
we're about to bury you.

306
00:28:13,920 --> 00:28:16,718
- Helen...
- What?

307
00:28:17,440 --> 00:28:19,670
We'll have something for you soon.

308
00:28:19,880 --> 00:28:24,556
- We only went to Cabrini today, and...
- Ah! Cabrini-Green.

309
00:28:25,600 --> 00:28:27,556
Candyman country.

310
00:28:29,040 --> 00:28:34,114
If you're after the hook man, read the
paper I wrote about him ten years ago.

311
00:28:34,320 --> 00:28:36,834
You do know the story, don't you?

312
00:28:37,520 --> 00:28:38,475
No...

313
00:28:39,520 --> 00:28:42,398
[loud laughter]

314
00:28:46,440 --> 00:28:48,396
Then how are you going to bury me?

315
00:28:52,640 --> 00:28:55,712
The legend first appeared in 1890.

316
00:28:57,200 --> 00:28:59,475
Candyman was the son of a slave.

317
00:29:00,640 --> 00:29:04,952
His father had amassed a considerable
fortune from designing a device

318
00:29:05,160 --> 00:29:08,038
for the mass-producing of shoes
after the Civil War.

319
00:29:09,920 --> 00:29:12,229
Candyman had been
sent to the best schools

320
00:29:12,440 --> 00:29:14,396
and had grown up in polite society.

321
00:29:16,760 --> 00:29:19,718
He had a prodigious talent
as an artist

322
00:29:21,200 --> 00:29:25,830
and was much sought after when it came
to the documenting of one's wealth

323
00:29:26,040 --> 00:29:28,679
and position in society in a portrait.

324
00:29:30,320 --> 00:29:33,118
It was in this latter capacity

325
00:29:33,320 --> 00:29:35,959
that he was commissioned
by a wealthy landowner

326
00:29:36,160 --> 00:29:38,833
to capture
his daughter's virginal beauty.

327
00:29:41,520 --> 00:29:43,829
Well, of course,
they fell deeply in love,

328
00:29:44,040 --> 00:29:46,759
and she became pregnant.

329
00:29:47,800 --> 00:29:49,631
Hmph.

330
00:29:49,840 --> 00:29:51,796
Poor Candyman.

331
00:29:55,520 --> 00:29:58,557
The father executed
a terrible revenge.

332
00:29:59,920 --> 00:30:02,559
He paid a pack of brutal hooligans
to do the deed.

333
00:30:04,680 --> 00:30:07,831
They chased Candyman
through the town to Cabrini-Green,

334
00:30:09,000 --> 00:30:13,596
where they proceeded to saw off
his right hand with a rusty blade.

335
00:30:15,200 --> 00:30:19,398
- No one came to his aid.
- [man screaming]

336
00:30:19,600 --> 00:30:22,319
But this was just the beginning
of his ordeal.

337
00:30:22,520 --> 00:30:28,152
Nearby there was an apiary. Dozens
of hives, filled with hungry bees.

338
00:30:28,360 --> 00:30:30,510
[screaming continues]

339
00:30:30,720 --> 00:30:34,156
They smashed the hives
and stole the honeycomb...

340
00:30:34,360 --> 00:30:37,477
...and smeared it
over his prone, naked body.

341
00:30:40,480 --> 00:30:43,756
Candyman was stung to death
by the bees.

342
00:30:45,520 --> 00:30:48,193
<i>They burned his body</i>
<i>on a giant pyre</i>

343
00:30:48,400 --> 00:30:51,153
<i>and then scattered his ashes</i>
<i>over Cabrini-Green.</i>

344
00:31:05,600 --> 00:31:06,555
Hello.

345
00:31:10,480 --> 00:31:11,879
Anne-Marie ain't in.

346
00:31:13,640 --> 00:31:17,713
- Are you sure?
- Yeah. She said you'd be back.

347
00:31:21,760 --> 00:31:23,512
[barking]

348
00:31:25,360 --> 00:31:27,396
What's your name?

349
00:31:27,600 --> 00:31:28,953
Jake.

350
00:31:30,960 --> 00:31:33,520
Well, listen, Jake,
maybe you can help me out.

351
00:31:33,720 --> 00:31:36,996
I wanted to find out
about that woman who got killed.

352
00:31:37,200 --> 00:31:39,555
Do you know anything about that?

353
00:31:39,760 --> 00:31:41,432
Her name was Ruthie Jean.

354
00:31:42,240 --> 00:31:44,515
I don't know nothin'.

355
00:31:44,720 --> 00:31:46,517
Did anybody else talk about it?

356
00:31:49,760 --> 00:31:52,911
It's OK to talk to me, Jake.

357
00:31:56,640 --> 00:31:58,596
Cos I'm not a cop.

358
00:31:59,480 --> 00:32:03,109
- So nobody's gonna get in trouble.
- I can't say nothin',

359
00:32:03,320 --> 00:32:05,276
or Candyman'll get me.

360
00:32:06,600 --> 00:32:08,556
Candyman, huh?

361
00:32:09,880 --> 00:32:11,711
You scared of him?

362
00:32:11,920 --> 00:32:14,036
I ain't scared of nobody.

363
00:32:14,240 --> 00:32:17,198
But you're crazy
walkin' here on your own.

364
00:32:17,400 --> 00:32:20,278
- It ain't safe around here.
- Yeah, I know.

365
00:32:23,400 --> 00:32:26,153
But I don't scare
too easy either, Jake.

366
00:32:28,560 --> 00:32:31,393
You know, you don't have to tell me.

367
00:32:31,600 --> 00:32:33,556
You could just show me.

368
00:32:35,040 --> 00:32:38,919
And if you show me where Candyman is,
I'll make you a promise.

369
00:32:39,760 --> 00:32:41,716
It'll be our secret.

370
00:32:46,320 --> 00:32:48,276
Unless you're too scared.

371
00:32:59,680 --> 00:33:03,150
- Somebody building a bonfire?
- Yeah, for the party.

372
00:33:21,000 --> 00:33:22,991
In there.

373
00:33:23,200 --> 00:33:26,112
- Candyman's in there?
- My friend Charlie says so.

374
00:33:26,320 --> 00:33:28,709
A boy got killed there.

375
00:33:32,000 --> 00:33:33,956
- Who was he?
- Ain't sure.

376
00:33:34,160 --> 00:33:36,071
Charlie tell me he was weird.

377
00:33:36,280 --> 00:33:39,272
- He was crazy?
- No, a retard.

378
00:33:40,400 --> 00:33:42,356
His mom was in the store.

379
00:33:44,800 --> 00:33:47,234
And the boy
needed to go to the bathroom.

380
00:33:48,600 --> 00:33:52,388
His mom was takin' her time,
choosin' this, lookin' at that.

381
00:33:52,600 --> 00:33:55,672
So the boy started moanin'.
His mom get mad at him.

382
00:33:55,880 --> 00:33:57,632
Sent him across the street.

383
00:33:57,840 --> 00:34:01,310
His mom's at the checkout.
She hears her boy screamin'.

384
00:34:01,520 --> 00:34:04,398
[boy] Mommy! Mommy!

385
00:34:04,600 --> 00:34:08,752
There's a big tough guy.
He runs over to check it out.

386
00:34:10,400 --> 00:34:12,868
<i>Come out of there shakin' and cryin'.</i>

387
00:34:13,280 --> 00:34:15,589
He only been in there five seconds.

388
00:34:16,560 --> 00:34:19,836
Come out of there
and his hair turned white.

389
00:34:20,800 --> 00:34:22,950
I mean, it turned white, just like that.

390
00:34:24,000 --> 00:34:25,592
Was the boy murdered?

391
00:34:25,800 --> 00:34:30,715
Worse. He's lyin' on the floor
in a pool of blood, holdin' himself.

392
00:34:30,920 --> 00:34:35,072
[screaming] Mommy! Mommy!

393
00:34:36,280 --> 00:34:38,874
They found it floating in a toilet.

394
00:34:39,080 --> 00:34:41,913
Can't fix that. Better off dead.

395
00:34:43,320 --> 00:34:44,878
Did Candyman do this?

396
00:34:52,040 --> 00:34:55,157
- Listen, you wait here for me, OK?
- OK.

397
00:35:12,040 --> 00:35:12,995
Hello?

398
00:35:16,080 --> 00:35:18,036
[gasps]

399
00:35:24,640 --> 00:35:26,596
[coughing]

400
00:36:10,320 --> 00:36:11,878
[buzzing]

401
00:36:26,640 --> 00:36:28,392
Candyman.

402
00:36:45,120 --> 00:36:47,076
Oh, excuse me.

403
00:36:47,280 --> 00:36:49,669
I'm done here.
I'll just get out of your way.

404
00:36:55,960 --> 00:36:58,428
I don't want to interfere
with your business.

405
00:36:58,640 --> 00:37:02,349
I'm not a cop.
I'm from the University of Illinois.

406
00:37:04,040 --> 00:37:07,715
And...
I'll just get out of your way.

407
00:37:07,920 --> 00:37:10,229
Hey, come on! Let me go!

408
00:37:10,440 --> 00:37:12,396
You're not being very smart.

409
00:37:12,600 --> 00:37:15,353
My colleagues know where I am
and are expecting me.

410
00:37:15,560 --> 00:37:16,993
Now let me go!

411
00:37:19,960 --> 00:37:22,838
I hear you're lookin'
for Candyman, bitch.

412
00:37:24,400 --> 00:37:26,231
Well, you found him.

413
00:37:26,440 --> 00:37:29,193
[blows landing]

414
00:37:32,840 --> 00:37:34,796
[laughing]

415
00:37:42,040 --> 00:37:44,679
We hear you're looking
for Candyman, bitch.

416
00:37:44,880 --> 00:37:46,836
[man] Step back.

417
00:37:49,840 --> 00:37:52,308
Number four,
step forward and say the line.

418
00:37:52,520 --> 00:37:55,273
We hear you're looking
for Candyman, bitch.

419
00:37:55,480 --> 00:37:57,436
[man] Step back.

420
00:37:59,800 --> 00:38:02,189
Number five,
step forward and say the line.

421
00:38:02,400 --> 00:38:04,868
We hear you're looking
for Candyman, bitch.

422
00:38:05,080 --> 00:38:07,036
[man] Step back. Take 'em out.

423
00:38:19,160 --> 00:38:21,720
- Number five.
- Good work.

424
00:38:26,280 --> 00:38:29,352
- How'd you catch him?
- We swept the place.

425
00:38:29,560 --> 00:38:31,551
Start from the top floor, work down.

426
00:38:31,760 --> 00:38:33,830
That way you can flush them all out.

427
00:38:34,040 --> 00:38:36,156
Whole of Cabrini's locked down now.

428
00:38:36,360 --> 00:38:38,874
You're lucky to be alive, Ms Lyle.

429
00:38:42,000 --> 00:38:44,912
- Did he kill Ruthie Jean?
- No question.

430
00:38:45,120 --> 00:38:49,477
Killed that poor kid as well.
He ran the Overlords.

431
00:38:49,680 --> 00:38:51,875
We knew everything about him.

432
00:38:52,080 --> 00:38:56,198
We didn't bring him in before
because no one would testify.

433
00:38:56,400 --> 00:38:59,870
We can't protect them down
at Cabrini-Green. They knew that.

434
00:39:01,840 --> 00:39:03,796
What about the little boy? Jake?

435
00:39:04,000 --> 00:39:06,434
We don't need him. We have you.

436
00:39:13,440 --> 00:39:15,396
Hey, Jake.

437
00:39:21,640 --> 00:39:24,074
I wanted to thank you
for saving my life.

438
00:39:24,280 --> 00:39:27,829
- I wanna go home.
- We'll get you outta here right away.

439
00:39:28,280 --> 00:39:31,033
- You did good.
- You said it was our secret.

440
00:39:31,240 --> 00:39:34,198
- You lied.
- It still is, Jake.

441
00:39:34,400 --> 00:39:36,789
You won't have to go to court.

442
00:39:38,600 --> 00:39:41,319
[whispers] Candyman will get me.

443
00:39:42,760 --> 00:39:44,398
Candyman isn't real.

444
00:39:44,600 --> 00:39:46,830
He's just a story.

445
00:39:47,040 --> 00:39:50,191
You know, like Dracula or Frankenstein.

446
00:39:51,720 --> 00:39:55,076
A bad man took his name
so he could scare us.

447
00:39:55,280 --> 00:39:57,953
Now he's locked up.
Everything's gonna be OK.

448
00:39:59,320 --> 00:40:01,276
Candyman ain't real?

449
00:40:02,880 --> 00:40:04,359
No.

450
00:40:10,280 --> 00:40:12,714
- Hey!
- Slow down!

451
00:40:12,920 --> 00:40:16,595
- You're supposed to be the invalid.
- No, it's better. Look. See?

452
00:40:16,800 --> 00:40:20,110
- Yeah, it looks great.
- Come and sit.

453
00:40:34,640 --> 00:40:37,791
- You haven't eaten already, have you?
- No, of course not.

454
00:40:38,680 --> 00:40:39,669
OK, good.

455
00:40:56,680 --> 00:40:59,274
Hey, welcome back.

456
00:41:00,200 --> 00:41:02,156
- Thanks.
- Let me see.

457
00:41:03,880 --> 00:41:06,633
I'm so glad you're OK.
I would've totally freaked.

458
00:41:06,840 --> 00:41:10,913
You know what bugs me? Two people
get murdered, and the cops do nothing.

459
00:41:11,120 --> 00:41:14,192
A white woman's attacked,
and they lock the place down.

460
00:41:14,400 --> 00:41:16,595
Yeah, I know,
but this was a bad guy.

461
00:41:16,800 --> 00:41:20,190
You got him put away.
That's all that matters.

462
00:41:20,400 --> 00:41:22,834
Oh! I've got a surprise for you.

463
00:41:23,040 --> 00:41:25,508
- What?
- You're not gonna believe it.

464
00:41:27,920 --> 00:41:31,629
- The pictures.
- A friend of mine saved most of them.

465
00:41:33,040 --> 00:41:36,112
I'd written them off.
The camera was smashed.

466
00:41:36,320 --> 00:41:39,118
And I've been talking
to some publishers.

467
00:41:39,320 --> 00:41:42,756
There's a lot of interest
since you made the local section.

468
00:41:42,960 --> 00:41:44,996
We're gonna be published.

469
00:41:45,200 --> 00:41:47,953
I'll come over tomorrow,
and we'll get started.

470
00:41:48,160 --> 00:41:50,116
- Yeah.
- OK.

471
00:41:59,480 --> 00:42:01,436
[horn beeping]

472
00:42:27,920 --> 00:42:29,876
[distorted man's voice] Helen...

473
00:42:31,640 --> 00:42:32,914
Yes.

474
00:42:33,120 --> 00:42:35,076
Helen...

475
00:42:42,360 --> 00:42:44,112
Who is that?

476
00:42:47,400 --> 00:42:49,152
Who is that?

477
00:42:51,360 --> 00:42:52,759
Helen...

478
00:42:52,960 --> 00:42:54,916
I came for you.

479
00:43:14,880 --> 00:43:16,393
Do I know you?

480
00:43:16,600 --> 00:43:18,079
No...

481
00:43:18,280 --> 00:43:21,750
No, but you doubted me.

482
00:43:22,640 --> 00:43:27,111
- I'm sorry. I have to go.
- No need to leave yet.

483
00:43:31,480 --> 00:43:33,710
But I'm late.

484
00:43:33,920 --> 00:43:36,753
You are not content
with the stories,

485
00:43:36,960 --> 00:43:39,758
so I was obliged to come.

486
00:43:43,920 --> 00:43:45,035
[sighs]

487
00:43:46,640 --> 00:43:48,278
Be my victim.

488
00:43:51,840 --> 00:43:53,796
Be my victim.

489
00:43:57,120 --> 00:44:00,157
I am the writing on the wall,

